    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Hyaluronic Acid Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What does hyaluronic acid do for your skin?</summary><p>HA binds up to 1,000 times its weight in water, hydrating the skin from within. It fills the extracellular matrix between collagen and elastin, creating plump, dewy, youthful-looking skin. Skin HA decreases by about 50% by age 50.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do oral hyaluronic acid supplements actually work?</summary><p>Yes. A meta-analysis of 13 trials found oral HA at 80-200mg daily significantly improved skin hydration and reduced wrinkle depth. HA fragments from the gut stimulate fibroblasts to produce more endogenous HA and collagen.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much hyaluronic acid should I take daily?</summary><p>80-200mg daily, based on clinical trial evidence. Most benefits appear at 120-200mg over 4-12 weeks of consistent use.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does molecular weight of HA matter?</summary><p>Yes. Low-to-medium MW (50-300 kDa) is better absorbed from the gut. High MW provides greater hydration once in the skin. Some products use a blend for both benefits.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long does it take for HA gummies to work?</summary><p>Measurable improvements in skin hydration within 2-4 weeks. Wrinkle reduction and elasticity improvements at 6-8 weeks. Maximum benefits at 8-12 weeks of daily use.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take hyaluronic acid with collagen?</summary><p>Yes — they are synergistic. HA provides hydration while collagen provides structural support. The combination is more effective for skin health than either alone.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Is hyaluronic acid safe during pregnancy?</summary><p>Limited pregnancy data exists. HA is naturally present in the body and not known to be harmful, but consult your OB/GYN. Topical HA is generally considered safe.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does HA help with joint health?</summary><p>Yes. HA is a major synovial fluid component. Oral supplementation at 80-200mg daily reduced joint pain and improved function in OA patients across 13 RCTs.</p></details>

    <div class="warn-box"><span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span><p><strong>Important:</strong> Hyaluronic acid supplements are generally well-tolerated, but individuals with cancer or a history of cancer should consult their oncologist before supplementing, as HA plays a role in cell proliferation and some studies suggest it may influence tumor biology. Pregnant and nursing women should consult their healthcare provider.</p></div>

